IN PLAN MODE: I want a PLAN only (no implementation yet).

Create a single, seamless, comprehensive, and highly specific ATDD execution plan for this scope: <scope here>.

Hard requirements for the plan:
1) Must be issue-by-issue exhaustive. For EVERY identified gap/bug/improvement, include:
   - Issue ID + short title
   - Root cause summary
   - Exact production files to change
   - Exact existing test files/spec blocks to update (or justify new file)
   - Exact new/updated E2E test scenarios (Given/When/Then style)
   - Exact acceptance criteria (what must be true to mark done)

2) ATDD sequencing is mandatory per issue:
   - E2E acceptance tests first (red specs written; no need to run red)
   - Production changes
   - Green validation for related E2E
   - Unit/integration backfill only where needed

3) Must strictly follow:
   - docs/e2e-testing-rules.md
   - docs/unit-testing-rules.md
   - docs/integration-testing-rules.md
   - CLAUDE.md quality rules

4) Include a “Test Refactor Compliance” section:
   - Which existing E2E tests are shallow/non-compliant
   - How each will be merged/refactored to comply (>=2 user actions + meaningful outcomes, stable data-testid selectors, no brittle waits, state isolation)

5) Include execution commands in order:
   - quality gate first (`pnpm quality`)
   - related E2E runs (file-by-file)
   - related unit/integration runs
   - full related verification sequence

6) Include migration handling decision tree:
   - if schema changes needed -> exact migration workflow (local apply, seed sync, safe prod apply)
   - if not needed -> explicitly state “no migration expected” and verification step

7) Include Definition of Done checklist:
   - per issue DoD
   - global DoD (all related tests green, quality clean, behavior parity validated)

8) No generic wording. No placeholders like “update tests as needed”.
   - Must name concrete files and concrete scenario names.
   - If uncertain, state assumption explicitly and ask only critical questions.

Output format (strict):
A) Scope and assumptions
B) Issue matrix (one block per issue)
C) Detailed execution sequence (ordered steps)
D) Command plan
E) Risk/rollback notes
F) Definition of done
